2015-06-02 11:05:08	acidrainfall	looooooooooool
2015-06-02 11:06:17	<--	Draecos (~Draecos@58-7-95-88.dyn.iinet.net.au) has quit (Quit: This computer has gone to sleep)
2015-06-02 11:06:55	MerlinTHP	stpierre is also pretty good for bash pedantry.
2015-06-02 11:07:11	Evolution	indeed
2015-06-02 11:07:11	stpierre	i see nothing evil about that
2015-06-02 11:07:17	stpierre	i do it all the time
2015-06-02 11:07:38	Evolution	see, for you that's a valid statement.
2015-06-02 11:07:50	Evolution	for me, "I do it all the time" has an entirely different connotation
2015-06-02 11:08:15	Evolution	I'm trying to actively *not* be terrible with this.
2015-06-02 11:08:22	Evolution	it's confusing and frightening
2015-06-02 11:08:26	stpierre	that is the least terrible way to do it
2015-06-02 11:08:42	stpierre	more terrible would be: using something other than the retval to determine success; using output redirection instead of -q; failing to quote something; and so on.
2015-06-02 11:09:15	stpierre	what you have is, as far as i'm concerned, the single canonical correct way to structure a conditional with grep.
2015-06-02 11:09:24	Evolution	well, this is mangling selinux so... I was going to parse getenforce or sestatus
2015-06-02 11:09:32	acidrainfall	I've always figured the advantage to bash is that what it lacks natively can be accomplished with your binary of choice (e.g. grep)
2015-06-02 11:09:58	Evolution	but checking /sys/fs/selinux/enforce seems easier.
2015-06-02 11:10:59	stpierre	then you don't need grep at all
2015-06-02 11:11:27	stpierre	if [[ $(cat /sys/fs/selinux/enforce) == 0 ]]; then  # or 1, as appropriate
