2015-06-04 11:34:12	jokajak	fix the build or install portion
2015-06-04 11:35:01	Comnenus	Is this real?
2015-06-04 11:35:02	Comnenus	https://www.groupon.com/deals/1337-institute-of-technology-1-worcester?p=3&utm_source=channel_occasions_merchandising&utm_medium=email&sid=63be89c1-ce90-4bf4-82c7-258c1374afe6&division=worcester&user=83d1afadc3277283ac840da297f067dba63eccebf71f001707b954d401a2a9fd&date=20150604&s=body&c=deal-button-3_merchandising&d=deal-page&utm_campaign=63be89c1-ce90-4bf4-
2015-06-04 11:35:02	Comnenus	82c7-258c1374afe6
2015-06-04 11:35:07	Comnenus	holy shit that's a hurl.  sorry.
2015-06-04 11:35:07	sadmin	I can minipulate the prefix= to control where it gets installed. I thought %(_bindir) would == /bin but it seems to go to /usr/bin instead :|
2015-06-04 11:35:17	ashp	Zathrus: No idea, I suppose the argument is that you just... merge with another one? I don't think they have any idea in their own theory
2015-06-04 11:35:22	Comnenus	try that again.  this.  http://www.1337institute.com/
2015-06-04 11:35:25	MerlinTHP	sadmin: yes, that's what %{_bindir} means.
2015-06-04 11:35:52	jokajak	sadmin: you can use rpm —show-rc to see the variables
2015-06-04 11:35:57	MerlinTHP	--showrc
2015-06-04 11:36:00	sadmin	jokajak: nice! Thanks
2015-06-04 11:36:01	jokajak	er, showrc
2015-06-04 11:36:06	jokajak	MerlinTHP: thanks
2015-06-04 11:36:16	MerlinTHP	There aren't RPM macros for /bin and /sbin
2015-06-04 11:36:29	sadmin	Should I refrain from install in /bin then?
2015-06-04 11:36:36	MerlinTHP	Nope.
2015-06-04 11:36:47	MerlinTHP	It just means there aren't macros for it.
2015-06-04 11:36:59	MerlinTHP	$RPM_BUILD_ROOT/bin
2015-06-04 11:37:22	sadmin	Should i modify the prefix to be /?
2015-06-04 11:37:25	sadmin	Or that works too
2015-06-04 11:37:42	Midoshi27	Scenario: I had mounted one of my external backup drive (/dev/sdc1) and then some asshole disconnected it. Now whenever it is connected it's seen /dev/sdd1. This screws up my automatic usb backup script... Can I somehow reassociate sdd1 back to sdc1??
2015-06-04 11:37:43	MerlinTHP	Prefix being /usr is correct 99.9% of the time.
2015-06-04 11:37:57	-->	rharrison (~rharriso@cpe-45-37-250-9.nc.res.rr.com) has joined #rhel
2015-06-04 11:38:09	jokajak	Midoshi27: reboot
2015-06-04 11:39:23	Zathrus	sadmin: the better question is, why do you want it in /bin instead of /usr/bin? There are some things that should go in /bin, but for 99% of things, /usr/bin is correct
2015-06-04 11:40:18	Midoshi27	jokajak: haha ok will do. So simple!!
2015-06-04 11:40:35	<--	BenA (~Ben@unaffiliated/BenA) has quit (Quit: joined channel #quit, type /quit to join him)
2015-06-04 11:41:01	MerlinTHP	Midoshi27: the kernel should create a bunch of symlinks based on UUID, label, etc.  They're fixed.  You should use those instead.
2015-06-04 11:41:11	<--	rssfed23 (~rssfed23@cpc72445-sotn14-2-0-cust778.15-1.cable.virginm.net) has quit (Ping timeout: 258 seconds)
2015-06-04 11:41:31	<--	vwbusguy (~vwbusguy@fedora/vwbusguy) has quit (Read error: Connection reset by peer)
2015-06-04 11:41:59	sadmin	Zathrus: I'm sure my logic is flawed but it just seemed like most of the git binaries are in /bin and my package will be adding a git- binary...
2015-06-04 11:42:17	sadmin	but now that i look at it, those binaries are in both /bin and /usr/bin
2015-06-04 11:42:52	Midoshi27	jokajak: Worked like a charm, thanks
2015-06-04 11:43:00	MerlinTHP	sadmin: On rhel 7, /bin and /sbin are symlinks
2015-06-04 11:43:21	Zathrus	so everything that's in /bin is in /usr/bin :)
2015-06-04 11:43:26	sadmin	oh, bin is /usr/bin
2015-06-04 11:43:28	sadmin	:)
2015-06-04 11:43:32	sadmin	LOL
2015-06-04 11:44:12	Zathrus	sadmin: the same is true for /sbin and /usr/sbin
2015-06-04 11:46:24	sadmin	Thanks for the help. That really simplifies things
