2015-06-10 16:02:15	-->	geek_cl (~lletelier@186-79-8-82.baf.movistar.cl) has joined #rhel
2015-06-10 16:03:16	gaurdro	thekabal,  the kernel is already installed.  it's also a special class of package that's 'install only'
2015-06-10 16:03:52	thekabal	gaurdro> I know that, but on the machines that are behaving differently, it should offer the newer kernel as an upgrade available
2015-06-10 16:04:40	gaurdro	thekabal, you haven't asked it to upgrade anything.  you told it to install a package that *never* is upgraded.  getting an updated kernel means installing a new version.
2015-06-10 16:05:39	gaurdro	thekabal, if you want it to offer the newer version as an update, use yum update kernel
2015-06-10 16:06:53	grit	i wonder why they still use 2.6 kernel on rhel 6.6
2015-06-10 16:06:58	thekabal	Yum install packagename also updates a package, try it some time. I’ve been using RH for a very long time. But even doing yum update kernel says no packages marked for upgrade - when I know that both the package is old, there is a new version, AND other machines have a newer version
2015-06-10 16:07:00	grit	on desktop edition even
2015-06-10 16:07:04	grit	isn't that retarded?
2015-06-10 16:07:54	stpierre	no, it's stable
2015-06-10 16:08:14	thekabal	Does redhat subscription sometimes “hide” specific updates? Because that seems to be how yum is acting.
2015-06-10 16:08:15	gaurdro	thekabal, this is why I pointed out to you that the kernel is an install-only package.  it isn't updated.  run the yum update kernel,  it'll tell you it's installing a version and possibly erasing a version.
